         <abstract>
            <p>Since short-term portfolio volatility will seldom cause liquidity problems for the institutional investor concerned primarily with long-term results, it is sometimes suggested that he focus solely on the average level of annual returns. At any given level of the average, however, an increase in the range of year-to-year portfolio returns will reduce his long-run rate of appreciation. Thus the investor is well advised to be concerned with the range of short-term returns as well as the average level--and not merely because short-term losses are unpleasant.</p>
          </abstract>
